Now let me understand the issue better. Looking at the `EstridsInvocationEffect.apply` method more carefully:

```java
public boolean apply(Game game, Ability source) {
    Player player = game.getPlayer(source.getControllerId());
    Permanent permanent = source.getSourcePermanentIfItStillExists(game);
    if (permanent == null || player == null) {
        return false;
    }
    Card card = permanent.getMainCard();
    player.moveCards(permanent, Zone.EXILED, source, game);
    player.moveCards(card, Zone.BATTLEFIELD, source, game, false, false, true, null);
    return true;
}
```

The issue is that when the ability fires the second time, the permanent has already been returned from exile and is now a new copy. When `source.getSourcePermanentIfItStillExists(game)` is called, it returns the current permanent. Then `permanent.getMainCard()` gets the card that represents it. The problem is likely that the permanent no longer exists after `moveCards(permanent, Zone.EXILED, ...)` and then when we try to move `card` back to battlefield, things go wrong because of the way the copy effect works.

Let me look at how `moveCards` handles moving a permanent to exile and a card to battlefield:

